ilgrimage routes to the Sinai. When Muslim armies later began conquering the Middle East, Christians also labeled these new conquerors as Saracens, connecting Muslims to these pre-Islamic representations. This timely and relevant work builds a historical account of interreligious encounters in the ancient world, showing the Sinai as a crucible for forging long-lasting images of both Christians and Muslims, some of which endure today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianityzEgyptzSinai. 0aMonasticism and religious orderszEgyptzSinai. 0aNomadszEgyptzSinaixHistory. 0aPilgrims and pilgrimageszEgyptzSinai. 70(DE-601)1050498080(DE-588)4216372-9aBeduine2gnd 70(DE-601)1056422150(DE-588)4138490-8aWallfahrer2gnd 70(DE-601)1057492810(DE-588)4124227-0aSpätantike2gnd 70(DE-601)1063599400(DE-588)4010071-6aChrist2gnd 70(DE-601)1063930060(DE-588)4002528-7aAraber2gnd 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient african history.  aancient history.  aancient world.  abible.  abiblical narratives.  abiblical study.  achristian monks.  achristian settlements.  achristianity.  achristians.  aclassical.  acomparative religion.  adefense of pilgrimage.  aearly seventh century.  aegyptian history.  aindigenous nomadic population.  aislam.  alate antiquity.  amartyrdom.  amonasticism.  amuslim.  anomads.  areligious history.  areligious studies.  asaracens.  asinai peninsula.  aspiritual benefits of asceticism.  atransformation of the classical heritage series.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028377040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095952140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document